.TH "SnapRAID Log Format" 1
.SH NAME
snapraid_log \- SnapRAID Log Format
.SH DESCRIPTION 
This document describes the structured log tags output by SnapRAID,
which are designed to be used by tools monitoring the SnapRAID
processing state. The tags provide information in an easy\-to\-parse
format, ideal for automation and integration.
.PP
To capture these structured log tags, you must use the \`\-\-log\` option
with SnapRAID.
.PP
You can direct the output to a specific file, or force the output to
the standard output or standard error using the special arguments
\`>&1\` or \`>&2\`. Note that these arguments often need to be quoted on
the command line to prevent the shell from interpreting them.
.PP
Example:
.PP
.RS 4
snapraid status \-\-log \[dq]>&2\[dq]
.PD 0
.PD
.RE
.PP
The output tags strictly adhere to the following format:
.PP
NAME:VALUE:VALUE:VALUE...<EOL>
.PD 0
.PD
.TP
.B NAME
This is the primary tag identifier, always a lowercase string
without spaces (e.g., \`summary\`, \`block\`).
.TP
.B VALUE
Following the \`NAME\`, these can be additional sub\-identifiers,
descriptive names (like a disk name), or numeric/string data
values. They are separated by a colon \`:\`.
.TP
.B <EOL>
Each tag is terminated by an end\-of\-line character.
.PP
This document provides a summary of the tags generated by SnapRAID.
For the most detailed and up\-to\-date information regarding the meaning
and context of the values, it is recommended to check the source
code\'s \`log_tag()\` statements.
.PP
When a path is output, it is always escaped using a backslash (\\) as
the escape character.
.PP
The following characters are escaped into sequences:
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I The colon
is escaped to \\d.
.HP 4
.I The newline
is escaped to \\n.
.HP 4
.I The carriage return
is escaped to \\r.
.HP 4
.I The backslash
is escaped to \\\\.
.PD
.RE
.PP
Some tags are output only when the \`\-\-gui\` or \`\-\-gui\-verbose\` option
is used. They provide extra verbose state and runtime progress only
useful for a GUI interface.
.PP
Integer values are marked as \`uint\` when they are unsigned and as \`int\`
when they are signed. However, for practical purposes you can treat
all of them as signed integers.
All integer values should be assumed to be 64 bits wide, regardless
of the signed/unsigned marker.
Floating point values are marked as \`float\`.
.SH CONFIGURATION TAGS 
These tags report the memory usage and global configuration.
.TP
.B conf:file:<path>
Configuration file loaded (escaped).
.TP
.B conf:missing:
Operating without a configuration file.
.TP
.B blocksize:<bytes>
The configured block size in bytes (uint).
.TP
.B data:<disk_name>:<dir>:<uuid>
The data disks as defined in the configuration file.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <disk_name>
The assigned name of the disk.
.HP 4
.I <dir>
The directory entry point of the disk.
.HP 4
.I <uuid>
The UUID of the filesystem containing the dir.
.PD
.RE
.TP
.B mode:<raidname>
The RAID mode used. One of \`par1\`, \`par2\`, \`par3\`, \`par4\`,
\`par5\`, \`par6\` or \`parz\`. The number indicates the maximum
number of simultaneous disk failures the array can withstand.
.TP
.B <parity_level>[/<split_index>]:<path>:<uuid>
The parity files as defined in the configuration file.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <parity_level>[/<split_index>]
One of \`parity\`, \`2\-parity\`,
..., \`6\-parity\`. This corresponds to the level of redundancy.
In case of split parity, the parity name is followed
by \`/N\` to indicate the split index, where N starts
from 0. The \`/0\` is always omitted.
.HP 4
.I <path>
The path (escaped).
.HP 4
.I <uuid>
The UUID of the filesystem containing the path.
.PD
.RE
.TP
.B fsinfo_data:<disk_name>:<size>:<free>
The filesystem information of the specified data disk.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <size>
The size of the data disk (uint).
.HP 4
.I <free_size>
The free size in the data disk (uint).
.PD
.RE
.TP
.B fsinfo_parity:<parity_level>:<size>:<free>
The filesystem information of the specified parity disk.
In case of multiple splits this is the sum of the sizes of all
splits.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <size>
The size of the parity disk (uint).
.HP 4
.I <free_size>
The free size in the parity disk (uint).
.PD
.RE
.TP
.B fsinfo_data_split:<disk_name>:<size>:<free>:<type>:<label>
The filesystem information of the specified data disk.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <size>
The size of the data disk (uint).
.HP 4
.I <free_size>
The free size in the data disk (uint).
.HP 4
.I <type>
The filesystem type. A string like \`ext4\`, \`ntfs\`.
.HP 4
.I <label>
The label associated to the filesystem.
.PD
.RE
.TP
.B fsinfo_parity_split:<parity_level>[/<split_index>]:<size>:<free>:<type>:<label>
The filesystem information of the specified parity split.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <size>
The size of the parity disk (uint).
.HP 4
.I <free_size>
The free size in the parity disk (uint).
.HP 4
.I <type>
The filesystem type. A string like \`ext4\`, \`ntfs\`.
.HP 4
.I <label>
The label associated to the filesystem.
.PD
.RE
.TP
.B pool:<dir>
The configured dir to the pool mount point (escaped).
This is the optional mount point for the \'pool\' feature.
.TP
.B share:<dir>
The configured dir to the pool mount point (escaped).
This is the optional mount point for the \'share\' feature.
.TP
.B autosave:<bytes>
If the autosave feature is enabled, and after how many bytes
(uint). This specifies the interval for content file saving.
.TP
.B filter:<pattern>
All the active filters with their patterns. These patterns
exclude specific files or directories from the SnapRAID array.
.TP
.B filter:nohidden:
If the no\-hidden filter is enabled, meaning hidden files/directories
(starting with \'.\') are excluded from the array.
.SH CONTENT TAGS 
These tags report the information stored in the content file.
.TP
.B content:<path>
The absolute path to a content file being used (escaped).
Content files store the metadata (like file hashes and timestamps)
for the array.
.TP
.B content_write:<path>
The absolute path to a content file being written (escaped).
You will see multiple writes as the content file is saved in
multiple copies.
.TP
.B content_data:<disk_name>:<size>:<free_size>
The size of the data disk as stored in the content file.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <disk_name>
Name of the data disk.
.HP 4
.I <size>
The size of the data disk (uint).
.HP 4
.I <free_size>
The free size in the data disk (uint).
.PD
.RE
.TP
.B content_parity:<parity_level>:<size>:<free_size>
The size of the parity disk as stored in the content file.
In case of multiple splits this is the sum of the sizes of all
splits.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <parity_level>
Name of the parity.
.HP 4
.I <size>
The total size of the parity disk (uint).
.HP 4
.I <free_size>
The free size in the parity disk (uint).
.PD
.RE
.TP
.B content_data_split:<disk_name>:<uuid>
The data disk info as stored in the content file.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <disk_name>
Name of the data disk.
.HP 4
.I <uuid>
The UUID of the disk filesystem as stored in the
content file.
.PD
.RE
.TP
.B content_parity_split:<parity_level>[/<split_index>]:<uuid>:<path>:<size>
The parity split info as stored in the content file.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <parity_level>[/<split_index>]
One of \`parity\`, \`2\-parity\`,
..., \`6\-parity\`. This corresponds to the level of redundancy.
In case of split parity, the parity name is followed
by \`/N\` to indicate the split index, where N starts
from 0. The \`/0\` is always omitted.
.HP 4
.I <uuid>
The UUID of the disk containing the path.
.HP 4
.I <path>
The path of the parity file (escaped).
.HP 4
.I <size>
The size of the parity file (uint).
.PD
.RE
.TP
.B content_info:<kind>:<counter>
The counters in the content file. The \`kind\` is
one of the following:
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I file
The count of files.
.HP 4
.I hardlink
The counter of hardlinks.
.HP 4
.I symlink
The counter of symlinks.
.HP 4
.I dir_empty
The counter of empty directories.
.HP 4
.I block_bad
The counter of bad blocks. Bad blocks indicate data
or parity corruption.
.HP 4
.I block_rehash
The counter of blocks needing a rehash, usually
due to hash algorithm change.
.HP 4
.I block_unscrubbed
The counter of blocks that are unscrubbed
(just synced), meaning they have never been verified
since their first sync.
.HP 4
.I block_unsynced
The counter of blocks that are unsynced (need a sync),
meaning their parity data is out of date.
.HP 4
.I block
The total counter of blocks.
.PD
.RE
.TP
.B bucket_count:<uint>
Total number of info records listed with \`bucket\`.
.TP
.B bucket_block_count:<uint>
Total number of info blocks listed with \`bucket\`. This is the
sum of all the counters listed.
.TP
.B bucket:<time>:<count_scrubbed>:<count_new>
The info records.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <time>
Unix timestamp of the scrub/sync.
.HP 4
.I <count_scrubbed>
Number of blocks scrubbed at this timestamp.
.HP 4
.I <count_new>
Number of blocks that were synced at this
timestamp and haven\'t been scrubbed yet.
.PD
.RE
.SH DIAGNOSTICS TAGS 
.TP
.B version:<version>
The version of SnapRAID run.
.TP
.B unixtime:<time>
The current time in the unix format (uint), representing
seconds since the epoch.
.TP
.B time:<YYYY\-MM\-DD HH:MM:SS>
The current time in human format.
.TP
.B command:<command>
The command run. One of \`sync\`, \`scrub\`, \`check\`, \`fix\`, \`status\`, ...
.TP
.B argv:<number>:<argument>
All the arguments of the executable command. The 0 one is the
executable run.
.TP
.B memory:used:<bytes>
The total memory currently used by the application in bytes (uint).
.TP
.B memory:block:<bytes>
Size of the internal \`snapraid_block\` structure in bytes (uint).
.TP
.B memory:extent:<bytes>
Size of the internal \`snapraid_extent\` structure in bytes (uint).
.TP
.B memory:file:<bytes>
Size of the internal \`snapraid_file\` structure in bytes (uint).
.TP
.B memory:link:<bytes>
Size of the internal \`snapraid_link\` structure in bytes (uint).
.TP
.B memory:dir:<bytes>
Size of the internal \`snapraid_dir\` structure in bytes (uint).
.SH SCAN TAGS 
These tags report detected differences between the filesystem and the
content file. They are output for every discovered change.
.TP
.B scan:equal:<disk_name>:<path>
A file, link, or directory is equal (unchanged).
No action is required for this item.
Only produced when \`\-\-gui\-verbose\` option is used.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <disk_name>
Name of the data disk.
.HP 4
.I <path>
Path to the file/link relative to the disk mount
(escaped).
.PD
.RE
.TP
.B scan:add:<disk_name>:<path>
A new file or link was found that is not in the content file.
This item will be added to the array in a \`sync\`.
.TP
.B scan:remove:<disk_name>:<path>
A file or link has been removed from the filesystem
since the last sync.
.TP
.B scan:update:<disk_name>:<path>
A file or link has been updated (size, timestamp, or link target changed).
This item will have its content data blocks re\-hashed in a \`sync\`.
.TP
.B scan:move:<disk_name>:<old_path>:<new_path>
A file was moved on the same disk. This is an efficient operation
that only updates the path metadata without re\-hashing blocks.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <old_path>
The old path to the file (escaped).
.HP 4
.I <new_path>
The new path to the file (escaped).
.PD
.RE
.TP
.B scan:copy:<disk_name>:<path>:<source_disk>:<source_path>
A new file was found to be a copy of a file from another disk.
This is detected by matching file size and timestamp, and is an
efficient operation that avoids re\-hashing all blocks.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <source_disk>
The original file\'s disk.
.HP 4
.I <source_path>
The original file\'s location (escaped).
.PD
.RE
.TP
.B scan:restore:<disk_name>:<path>
A file\'s inode has changed but not its date\-time and size,
which suggests the file may be restored from backup.
The file won\'t be re\-hashed in \`sync\` as its precomputed hash
is assumed to be correct.
.PP
These tags provide a final count of all detected changes.
.TP
.B summary:equal:<count>
Total number of files and links whose metadata and data match
the current parity (uint).
.TP
.B summary:added:<count>
Total number of brand new files and links not present in the
last sync (uint).
.TP
.B summary:removed:<count>
Total number of files and links that existed in the last sync
but are now missing (uint).
.TP
.B summary:updated:<count>
Total number of existing files where the timestamp or size has
changed (uint).
.TP
.B summary:moved:<count>
Total number of files relocated to a new path or renamed but
retaining the same inode (uint).
.TP
.B summary:copied:<count>
Total number of new files created by copying an existing
protected file to a new path (uint).
.TP
.B summary:restored:<count>
Total number of new files matching a parity entry by
name/time/size but with a new inode (uint).
.TP
.B summary:exit:<status>
Logs the overall exit status of the command. The \`status\` is
one of the following:
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I equal
Indicates that no differences were found.
The array is already synchronized.
.HP 4
.I diff
Indicates that differences were found.
The array needs a \`sync\` operation.
.HP 4
.I unsynced
The array has an interrupted sync.
The array needs another \`sync\` operation.
.PD
.RE
.SH GENERAL PROGRESS AND EXECUTION TAGS 
These tags are used to report the runtime processing of the commands
\`sync\`, \`scrub\`, \`check\` and \`fix\`.
Only produced when \`\-\-gui\` option is used.
.TP
.B run:begin:<blockbegin>:<blockend>:<count>
A tag indicating the start of the command execution.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <blockbegin>
Starting block index (uint).
.HP 4
.I <blockend>
Ending block index + 1 (uint).
.HP 4
.I <count>
Number of blocks to process. It may be less
than <blockend> \- <blockbegin> + 1 if some blocks
are going to be skipped (uint).
.PD
.RE
.TP
.B run:end
A zero\-argument tag indicating the end of the command execution.
.TP
.B run:pos:<blockidx>:<blockdone>:<sizedone>:<perc>:<eta>:<speed_mbs>:<cpu>:<elapsed>:<temp>:<steady_temp>
Detailed progress information during command execution.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <blockidx>
Current block index position processed (uint).
.HP 4
.I <blockdone>
Number of blocks processed (uint).
.HP 4
.I <sizedone>
Current size processed (uint).
.HP 4
.I <perc>
Completion percentage (uint).
.HP 4
.I <eta>
Estimated time to completion in seconds. Empty if not
available (uint).
.HP 4
.I <speed_mbs>
Data processing speed in MB/s. Empty if not
available (uint).
.HP 4
.I <cpu>
CPU usage percentage. Empty if not available (uint).
.HP 4
.I <elapsed>
Elapsed time in seconds (uint).
.HP 4
.I <temp>
Current max temperature of the disks. Empty if not
available (uint).
.HP 4
.I <steady_temp>
Expected steady temperature of the disks.
Empty if not available (uint).
.PD
.RE
.TP
.B sigint:<blockidx>:<msg>
A user interruption (e.g., Ctrl+C) was signaled. The process
is gracefully aborting.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <blockidx>
Current block index position (uint).
.HP 4
.I <msg>
Text message exactly as it\'s printed on screen.
.PD
.RE
.TP
.B msg:<level>:<msg>
Messages printed to the screen.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <level>
One of \`fatal\`, \`fatal_hardware\`, \`error\`, \`error_hardware\`,
\`expected\`, \`status\`, \`progress\` or \`verbose\`.
.HP 4
.I fatal, fatal_hardware
A fatal error occurred. Program will
abort after this message.
The \`hardware\` one means that the problem was caused
by a hardware failure, like an Input/Output error
or a silent data error.
.HP 4
.I error, error_hardware
A generic error condition that doesn\'t
prevent the program to continue.
The \`hardware\` one means that the problem was caused
by a hardware failure, like an Input/Output error
or a silent data error.
.HP 4
.I expected
An expected error condition. At present it
happens only when using the \`\-m\` option with files
expected missing.
.HP 4
.I status
A status message, usually providing context or a summary.
.HP 4
.I progress
A progress message, often part of an ongoing operation.
.HP 4
.I verbose
A verbose informative message, only shown in verbose mode.
.HP 4
.I <msg>
Text message exactly as it\'s printed on screen.
.PD
.RE
.SH THERMAL TAGS 
The following tags are produced by the thermal monitoring functions
when SnapRAID is processing, typically during operations that involve
disk access.
.TP
.B thermal:ambient:device:<hwmon_dir>:<name>:<temp_file>:<label>:<temp>
Logs a temperature reading found in the system using the Linux
/sys/class/hwmon interface. Only present in Linux.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <hwmon_dir>
The hwmon directory name (e.g., hwmon0).
.HP 4
.I <name>
The name of the hwmon device (e.g., k10temp).
.HP 4
.I <temp_file>
The temperature file name (e.g., temp1_input).
.HP 4
.I <label>
The label associated with the temperature sensor (e.g., Tdie).
.HP 4
.I <temp>
The temperature reading in degrees Celsius.
.PD
.RE
.TP
.B thermal:ambient:candidate:<temp>
Reports a temperature reading that is a candidate for the
ambient temperature, used in the heating model calculation.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <temp>
The candidate temperature in degrees Celsius.
.PD
.RE
.TP
.B thermal:system:candidate:<temp>
Logs a temperature reading from a connected disk that is being
considered as a candidate for determining the ambient system
temperature.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <temp>
The current temperature read from the disk
(uint, degrees Celsius).
.PD
.RE
.TP
.B thermal:system:final:<temp>
Logs the final ambient system temperature calculated. This
value is the lowest valid temperature observed among all
candidates, representing the room temperature.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <temp>
The calculated ambient temperature in degrees Celsius.
.PD
.RE
.TP
.B thermal:current:<disk_name>[/<split_index>]:<device>:<temp>
Logs the most recent temperature reading for a specific disk
device.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <disk_name>[/<split_index>]
The configured name of the disk.
In case of split parity, the parity name is followed
by \`/N\` to indicate the split index, where N starts
from 0. The \`/0\` is always omitted.
.HP 4
.I <device>
The unique device ID (uint).
.HP 4
.I <temp>
The current temperature read from the disk in degrees
Celsius.
.PD
.RE
.TP
.B thermal:highest:<temp>
Logs the highest temperature observed among all monitored disks
in the current measurement cycle. This is used for thermal
throttling.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <temp>
The highest temperature observed in degrees Celsius.
.PD
.RE
.TP
.B thermal:heat:<disk_name>[/<split_index>]:<device>:<count>:<data_points>
Logs the entire history of temperature data points collected
so far for a specific disk, used for fitting the heating model.
Only monotone increasing temperatures are included in the history.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <device>
The unique device ID (uint).
.HP 4
.I <count>
The total number of collected data points (uint).
.HP 4
.I <data_points>
A comma\-separated list of temperature/time pairs.
Each pair is formatted as <temp>/<time_offset>.
.HP 4
.I <temp>
Temperature reading in degrees Celsius.
.HP 4
.I <time_offset>
Time offset from the start of the thermal
monitoring (uint, seconds).
.PD
.RE
.TP
.B thermal:params:<disk_name>[/<split_index>]:<device>:<k_heat>:<t_ambient>:<t_steady>:<rmse>:<r_squared>:<max_error>
Logs the estimated parameters for the exponential heating model
(fit using least squares) and associated quality metrics for a
specific disk.
The model is: T(t) = T_steady \- (T_steady \- T_0) e^(\-kt),
where T_0 is the initial temperature.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <device>
The unique device ID (uint).
.HP 4
.I <k_heat>
The heating rate constant, k (float).
.HP 4
.I <t_ambient>
The ambient temperature, T_ambient (float).
.HP 4
.I <t_steady>
The estimated steady\-state temperature, T_steady (float),
which is the maximum expected temperature of the disk.
.HP 4
.I <rmse>
Root Mean Square Error of the fit (float).
.HP 4
.I <r_squared>
Coefficient of determination (R^2) of the fit (float).
.HP 4
.I <max_error>
Maximum absolute error of the fit (float).
.PD
.RE
.TP
.B thermal:spindown
Indicates that the thermal alarm limit has been reached, and
the process is initiating a disk spindown to begin the
cooldown procedure, preventing overheating.
.TP
.B thermal:cooldown:<sleep_time>
Indicates the duration of the cooldown waiting period after
spindown.
.RS 4
.PD 0
.HP 4
.I <sleep_time>
The total time the system will wait for
cooldown (uint, seconds).
.PD
.RE
.TP
.B thermal:spinup
Indicates that the cooldown period is complete, and the disks
are being spun back up to resume the operation.
.SH COMMAND STATUS TAGS 
This section describes the tags output with the \`status\` command.
.SS Summary Tags 
These tags provide general information about the array configuration
and overall state.
.TP
.B summary:block_size:<uint>
The size of a block in bytes. This is the unit of parity
protection.
.TP
.B summary:parity_block_count:<uint>
The total number of blocks allocated for all parity levels
combined.
.TP
.B summary:parity_block_total:<name>:<uint>
Total blocks available for a specific parity level (e.g.,
\`parity\`, \`2\-parity\`).
.TP
.B summary:parity_block_free:<name>:<uint>
Free blocks available for a specific parity level.
.TP
.B summary:parity_block_free_min:<uint>
The minimum number of free blocks across all parity levels.
This determines the maximum size of data that can be added.
.TP
.B summary:file_count:<uint>
Total number of files in the array.
.TP
.B summary:file_block_count:<uint>
Total number of data blocks used by files.
.TP
.B summary:fragmented_file_count:<uint>
Total number of fragmented files, meaning files whose blocks
are not contiguous.
.TP
.B summary:excess_fragment_count:<uint>
Total number of excess fragments (one less than the total fragments).
This is a measure of data fragmentation overhead.
.TP
.B summary:zerosubsecond_file_count:<uint>
Total number of files with a zero sub\-second timestamp. This
can occur on certain filesystems and may affect change detection.
.TP
.B summary:file_size:<uint>
Total size of all files in bytes.
.TP
.B summary:parity_size:<uint>
Total size of allocated parity blocks in bytes.
.TP
.B summary:parity_size_max:<uint>
Maximum possible parity size (allocated + min free) in bytes.
This is the effective maximum protection size.
.TP
.B summary:hash:<name>
The current hash algorithm in use (e.g., \`sha256\`).
.TP
.B summary:prev_hash:<name>
The previous hash algorithm used, if a rehash is in progress.
.TP
.B summary:best_hash:<name>
The best hash algorithm for optimal performance based on
system capabilities.
.TP
.B summary:total_wasted:<uint>
Total wasted space (space on data disks exceeding parity
capacity) in bytes.
.TP
